After studying this a bit, it's straightforward to see
\mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M\oplus  N,P)\cong \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M,P)	imes \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(N,P)\hbox { as Abelian groups,}
and if R is commutative,
\mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M\oplus  N,P)\cong \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M,P)\oplus \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(N,P)\hbox { as }R\hbox {-modules.}
If we denote \Phi \colon \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M\oplus  N,P)	o \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M,P)\oplus \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(N,P) for this mapping, we just need to check:

Let \varphi _{1}\in \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M,P) and \varphi _{2}\in \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(N,P). We want to show there is a unique element of \varphi \in \mathop {	extrm {Hom}}
olimits _{R}(M\oplus N,P) such that \Phi (\varphi )=(\varphi _{1},\varphi _{2}). We see that there exists a function \phi such that for any m\in M and n\in N, \varphi _{1}(m)+\varphi _{2}(n)=\varphi (m,n). We need to check it is R-linear: \Phi (\varphi _{1},\varphi _{2})(m,n)=\varphi _{1}(m)+\varphi _{2}(n). This is straightforward.

